id about the Members of the Shura -- tAbū Bakr’s Designation of ʿUmar as His Successor -- tThe Oath of Fealty Pledged to Abū Bakr -- tThe Expedition of Dhāt al-Salāsil and the Story of ʿAlī and Muʿāwiyah -- tThe Story of al-Ḥajjāj ibn ʿIlāṭ -- tThe Dispute between ʿAlī and al-ʿAbbās -- tThe Story of Abū Luʾluʾah, ʿUmar’s Assassin -- tThe Story of the Shura -- tThe Expeditions to al-Qādisiyyah and Elsewhere -- tThe Marriage of Fāṭimah -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Names, Places, and Terms -- tGenealogical Table of the Quraysh of Mecca -- tBibliography -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex -- tAbout the NYU Abu Dhabi Institute -- tAbout the Typefaces -- tAbout the Editor-Translator0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the earliest surviving biographies of Prophet Muḥammad, translated into readable, modern English for the first timeThe Expeditions is one of the oldest biographies of the Prophet Muḥammad to survive into the modern era. Its primary author, Maʿmar ibn Rāshid (96-153/714-770), was a prominent scholar from Basra in southern Iraq who was revered for his learning in prophetic traditions, Islamic law, and the interpretation of the Qurʾan. This fascinating foundational seminal work contains stories handed down by Maʿmar to his most prominent pupil, ʿAbd al-Razzāq of Sanaa, relating Muḥammad’s early life and prophetic career as well as the adventures and tribulations of his earliest followers during their conquest of the Near East.Edited from a sole surviving manuscript, the Arabic text offers numerous improved readings over those of previous editions, including detailed notes on the text’s transmission and variants as found in later works. This new translation, which renders the original into readable, modern English for the first time, is accompanied by numerous annotations elucidating the cultural, religious, and historical contexts of the events and individuals described within its pages.The Expeditions represents an important testimony to the earliest Muslims’ memory of the lives of Muḥammad and his companions, and is an indispensable text for gaining insight into the historical biography of both the Prophet and the rise of the Islamic empire.A bilingual Arabic-English edition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAnthony, Sean W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaleem, M.A.S. Abdel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814738290.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814738290423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814738290/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles